### Description

I don't know if this is by design, but the behavior is very different from when working with plain observables or promises. 
Consider a simple component
```
export class TestComponent  {
  stuff: ResourceRef<string | undefined>;
  constructor(service: StuffService) {
    this.stuff = resource({
      loader: () => firstValueFrom(service.stuff$)
    });
  }
}
```
If we write a simple test case that wants to check the state before the first resource value is loaded, the call to `whenStable()` won't resolve and the test case times out.
```
  const stuff$ = new ReplaySubject<string>(1);
  await TestBed.configureTestingModule({
      imports: [TestComponent],
      providers: [{
        provide: StuffService, useValue: { stuff$ }
      }]
  }).compileComponents();

  const fixture = TestBed.createComponent(TestComponent);
  fixture.detectChanges();
  await fixture.whenStable();
  expect(componentIsInStateBeforeStuffIsLoaded()).toBeTrue();
  stuff$.next('hello');
  fixture.detectChanges();
  await fixture.whenStable();
  expect(componentIsInStateAfterStuffIsLoaded()).toBeTrue();
```
The same happens with `rxResource`.

I would consider a component to be in a stable state while `resource` is loading the next value. At least it was always the case with asynchronous processes that it's fine to call `fixture.whenStable()` as many times you want. 

This example shows the different behavior when using resource or and async pipe on the source observable directly: https://stackblitz.com/edit/stackblitz-starters-yklwg5m5?file=src%2Fmain.ts

